<div id="review_2948423214" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2948423214" />
    <a title="Yun" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30181442-yun"><img alt="Yun" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1631406130p2/30181442.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2948423214?book_show_action=true">Aug 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Yun" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Yun" href="/user/show/30181442-yun">Yun</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780062073563" href="/book/show/9618464-the-murder-of-roger-ackroyd">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2948423214" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12341918179705854095">Even among Agatha Christie&apos;s amazing murder mysteries, <i>The Murder of Roger Ackroyd</i> stands out as one of the most extraordinary. I first read it more than 20 years ago in high school, and was so gobsmacked by the ending that I remembered it through all these years. Recently, I wanted to reread it and see if I still love it just as much, even though I already know the ending going in. And sure enough, it&apos;s just as brilliant as I remembered.<br/><br/>This story has all the characteristics that make an Agatha</span>
  <span id="freeText12341918179705854095" style="display:none">Even among Agatha Christie's amazing murder mysteries, <i>The Murder of Roger Ackroyd</i> stands out as one of the most extraordinary. I first read it more than 20 years ago in high school, and was so gobsmacked by the ending that I remembered it through all these years. Recently, I wanted to reread it and see if I still love it just as much, even though I already know the ending going in. And sure enough, it's just as brilliant as I remembered.<br /><br />This story has all the characteristics that make an Agatha Christie whodunnit remarkable: a confounding murder, a small but seemingly unlikely list of suspects, an abundance of secrets and red herrings everywhere, and an ending that will leave you astonished. It was really fun to revisit this story that has stood out in my memory for so long. <br /><br />In many ways, Agatha Christie was a pioneer in her genre, and this story is one example where you can see her influence in the books that have come since then. For me, she remains the undisputed queen. I only wish I can scrub my memory so I can enjoy this story over and over again.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12341918179705854095" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


